title: For Sale:  NORINKO NHM-91 AK 7.62x39 NEW UNFIRED
postcontent:
NEW --- UNFIRED --- Norinco, model NHM91, Imported by China Sports Inc. ONT CA as marked on receiver. Chambered in 7.62x39. 21" barrel with an adjustable rear sight and Bi-Pod.

The NHM-91, a version of the RPK, is built on a 1.5mm stamped receiver, making it heavier than the typical 1mm stamped receiver, resulting in better felt and controlled recoil. The longer barrel gives the NHM-91 a longer sight radius, resulting in more accurate shots.

The NHM-91 comes from the factory with a front barrel bi-pod, one 5 round magazine. The NHM-91 does not come from the factory with a bayonet lug as this would interfere with the location of the bi-pod. The barrel is threaded and capped off with a thread protector, however, the retention clip is not spring activated and therefore welded onto the threads. It is, however, possible to remove the retention clip to add on a muzzle compensator.

Most notably, the RPK has a heavier and longer barrel than an AKM. This allowed the Full Auto Machine Gun version of the RPK to fire for extended periods of time without major loss in accuracy due to the barrel heating up. The chrome-lined barrel is permanently fixed to the receiver, and cannot be replaced in the field. It is fitted with a new front sight base, gas block (lacks the bayonet lug). The barrel also features a folding bipod, mounted near the muzzle, and a front sight base with a lug that limits the bipod's rotation around the axis of barrel. The barrel's muzzle is threaded, enabling the use of muzzle devices such as flash hiders, compensators, and blank-firing adapters. When a muzzle device is not being used, the threads on the muzzle can be covered by a thread protector. The barrel is pinned to the receiver in a modified trunnion, reinforced by ribbing, and is slightly wider than the trunnion used on standard AKM type rifles. Symmetrical bulges on both sides of the front trunnion ensure proper fit inside the receiver.

The RPK's receiver cover is stamped from a smooth 1.5mm sheet of steel (compared to the 1 mm sheet metal receiver cover used on standard AKM rifles). Interchangeability of parts between the RPK and AKM is moderate.

The RPK uses a modified AKM recoil spring assembly. It consists of a rear spring guide rod from the AK, and a new forward flat guide rod and coil spring.

The weapon can use standard AKM detachable box magazines.

postcontent:
Braztech Rossi 7.62x39 single shot.  Its been very well taken care of, there is no rust anywhere on this rifle, its in excellent shape. The scope is a Center Point 4x16x50, with IR, AO, flip up covers.
I reloaded for this rifle and got some good accuracy with it. With the twist rate of this barrel it prefers light bullets (130gr and under).  I sluged the barrel and its a .308 bore with a 1 in 12 twist.
So far I have found this rifle likes 110gr Hornady V-max and Hornady 110gr Soft Point bullets. It also likes 100gr Hornady Short Jacket and Berrys 100gr Plated FMJ, both very cheap (economical). The powders I used where AA1680 for the Hornady bullets and Trail Boss for the Berrys.  I will share my load data with the buyer if they want, but I will not post it here, or tell anyone else.
I used it mostly for coyote hunting and ground hogs with the V-Max loads, and took a deer last season with the 110gr SP load.
Its a very light and economical rifle to shoot and I have enjoyed it a lot, but I have moved on to other projects and rarely shoot it anymore.
These are not manufactured anymore so they are rare in this caliber.

I live in Smithville, but I'm willing to travel to Cookeville, Lebanon, Sparta, or McMinnville to meet halfway.

title: For Sale:  Double barrel derringer in .45LC/.410
postcontent:
Took this gun in trade from a friend and don't have a use for it.  It appears to be in very good condition and everything functions correctly on it.

"FMJ" brand double barreled derringer.  This was made by the same company that mass produced MAC submachineguns before the 1986 ban.  It's more functional than pretty, but has its own aesthetic appeal.

Two barrels, with a selector on the hammer for which barrel to fire.  Single action--cock it and fire.  Has a safety, which must be engaged to swing open the barrels.

Each barrel can take either a .45LC cartridge or a .410 shot shell.  The barrels have a little rifling in them so it is classified as a pistol, not a shotgun.

This is a perfect little hold-out belly gun for short range protection, or great for throwing in your pocket when walking around the farm to protect against snakes.

I'm sure it kicks like a mule with full strength .45LC cartridges, but if you ever have to use it, you won't care.  Would have much less recoil with lower power .410 shells.

Interested in a straight up sale or trades.  Will entertain any trades on other firearms, but would prefer a straight-up trade to anything .22 (pistol or rifle) or a single-shot shotgun.

title: For Sale:  COLT  LE6920MP  M4 CARBINE---BRAND NEW
postcontent:
The Colt 6920MP-B is probably one of the best out-of-the-box AR-15s available.  Various police forces use them due to their reliability and performance, and that is often the same reason civilians purchase them.  They group well, perform well, and can handle being dirtied up some.  They are compact and lightweight, so they would make for a great multi-purpose carbine.  Just handling this one almost makes me want to buy one.  If you are in the market for an AR-15 but do not feel as though you would trust yourself with getting the best quality parts to do a build-it-yourself, the Colt 6920MP-B is probably one of your best choices.  They are more expensive than other AR-15s that are capable out-of-the-box, but the quality and fit of the Colt can't be matched.  You can tell they come from the same factory as the military rifles; the left side of the magazine well is even stamped "M4 CARBINE."  So, again, if you're wanting a good-to-go-out-of-the-box AR-15, I highly recommend the Colt SP 6920MP-B.
